{'html': '<!DOCTYPE HTML PUBLIC "-//W3C//DTD HTML 4.01 Transitional//EN">\r<html>\r<head>\r<title>e s c a p e</title>\r<meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=iso-8859-1">\r<meta name="description" content="esc-design, interaction design for dynamic interactive environments, 7c Sunderland Terrace, London W2 5PA, UK">\r<meta name="keywords" content=" escape design, esc design, architecture, design, interaction, dynamic interactive environments, performance, performativity, Mixed Reality, Augmented Reality, games, playful interaction, Mette Ramsgard Thomsen, Jesper Mortensen, bartlett, ucl, university of brighton, brighton, London">\r<script language="JavaScript" type="text/JavaScript">\r<!--\r\rfunction MM_reloadPage(init) {  //reloads the window if Nav4 resized\r  if (init==true) with (navigator) {if ((appName=="Netscape")&&(parseInt(appVersion)==4)) {\r    document.MM_pgW=innerWidth; document.MM_pgH=innerHeight; onresize=MM_reloadPage; }}\r  else if (innerWidth!=document.MM_pgW || innerHeight!=document.MM_pgH) location.reload();\r}\rMM_reloadPage(true);\r//-->\r</script>\r<link href="text_research.css" rel="stylesheet" type="text/css">\r</head>\r\r<body bgcolor="#999999" text="#FFFFFF">\r<div id="Layer1" style="position:absolute; left:0px; top:188px; width:1300px; height:44px; z-index:1"><img src="research/images/titlebar.gif" width="1300" height="44" border="0" usemap="#Map"> \r<map name="Map">\r    <area shape="rect" coords="781,17,874,35" href="presencia.html">\r    <area shape="rect" coords="659,15,752,35" href="crossings.html">\r    <area shape="rect" coords="509,15,632,36" href="kaleidoscope.html">\r    <area shape="rect" coords="373,18,471,36" href="earthdiver.html">\r    <area shape="rect" coords="30,1,272,38" href="../index.html">\r  </map>\r</div>\r<div id="Layer2" style="position:absolute; left:430px; top:270; width:450; height:850; z-index:2"> \r  <h1>Kaleidoscope: Programming ideas</h1>\r    \r  <p>The idea for <i>Kaleidoscope </i><span style=\'font-style:\rnormal\'>is to build a learning interface where the joint environment of user, \r    interface and digital dimension are considered as one intelligent place. </span><o:p></o:p></p>\r    \r  <P>In programming this we are developing a disjointed architecture which allows \r    the individual programs to be combined independently. This allows us to explore \r    the programs in respect to the follow up projects.<o:p></o:p></p>\r    \r  <P><i>Kaleidoscope </i><span style=\'font-style:normal\'>is designed \r    as a four part program: </span><o:p></o:p><o:p></o:p></p>\r  <table width="100%" border="1" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r    <tr valign="top"> \r      <td width="25%"> \r        <P>Part 1:Tracker</p></td>\r      <td width="25%"> \r        <P>Part 2:Behaviour Interpreter</p></td>\r      <td width="25%"> \r        <P>Part 3:Dynamic Feedback Mapper</p></td>\r      <td width="25%"> \r        <P>Part 4:Dynamic Interactive Environment </p></td>\r    </tr>\r    <tr valign="top"> \r      <td><P>The interface can essentially be any interface giving a stream of \r          input to the Behaviour Interpreter</p></td>\r      <td><P>1) Isolates and defines moment in the data as recognised \'actions\'. \r          <o:p></o:p><br>\r          <br>\r          2) Defines a (finite) list of recognised behaviours which is dynamically \r          updated over time by means of the data sent from the Dynamic Feedback \r          Mapper.</p></td>\r      <td><P>1) Creates dynamic mappings to the output parameters of the Dynamic \r          Interactive Environment. <o:p></o:p><br>\r          <br>\r          2) Defines the fitness function and feeds it back to the Behaviour Interpreter. \r          The fitness function is determined by the users repetition of action: \r          the more an action is repeated the more asserted it becomes.</p></td>\r      <td><P>1) The digital environment is defined through a set of parameters \r          for action. The parameters are open and combinable.<o:p></o:p><br>\r          <br>\r          2) The Dynamic Interactive Environment renders the environment.</p></td>\r    </tr>\r    <tr valign="top"> \r      <td><P>Passes on:<br>\r          raw tracking data</p></td>\r      <td><P>Passes on:<br>\r          defined behaviours</p></td>\r      <td><P>Passes on:<br>\r          Fitness function for the Behaviour Interpreter and mapping of behaviours \r          to output parameters for Dynamic Interactive Environment</p></td>\r      <td><P>Passes on:<br>\r          visualisation of the environment </p></td>\r    </tr>\r    <tr valign="top"> \r      <td>&nbsp;</td>\r      <td><P>Receives:<br>\r          Fitness function from Dynamic Feedback Mapper</p></td>\r      <td>&nbsp;</td>\r      <td>&nbsp;</td>\r    </tr>\r    <tr valign="top"> \r      <td><P>In the first stage this will be the screen tracker from <i>Spawn</i></p></td>\r      <td><P>In the first stage we are conceiving this as using a fuzzy pattern \r          recognition.</p></td>\r      <td><P>The most important thing for the Dynamic Feedback Mapper is the notion \r          of tunability. It is essential that the dynamic mappings can be tuned \r          so as to give the user a more or less intuitive experience.</p></td>\r      <td><P>In <i>Kaleidoscope</i><span style=\'font-style:normal\'> the rendering \r          will happen in passive stereoscopic projection.</span></p></td>\r    </tr>\r  </table>\r  <P><o:p></o:p></p>\r    \r  <P>Further requirements for the program is that the fuzzyness of the Behaviour \r    Interpreter and the mapping of the Dynamic Feedback Mapper can be adjusted \r    and tuned. It will be essential for the project that the looseness by which \r    the environment learns about the user\'s actions can be adjusted, allowing \r    for more or less \xd4intuitive\' pre-setups to define the learning curve of the \r    user. &nbsp; <o:p></o:p></p>\r    <h2>Ideas</h2>\r    <P><b><i>Forgetting</i></b><span style=\'font-weight:normal;\rfont-style:normal\'>: that the system forgets actions which are not repeated</span></p>\r    <P><b><i>Exaggeration: </i></b><span style=\'font-weight:normal;\rfont-style:normal\'>the idea that as actions are repeated they become more and \r      more exaggerated - allowing the user to sense of a firmness to the defined \r      behaviour.</span></p>\r    <P><b><i>Randomness/noise</i></b><span style=\'font-weight:normal;\rfont-style:normal\'>: that the system remains fresh by holding a certain sense \r      of randomness to the interaction</span></p>\r    <P><b><i>Knowledge transfer</i></b><span style=\'font-weight:\rnormal;font-style:normal\'>: that the system remembers actions from past users?</span></p>\r    <P><b><i>Soft interaction</i></b><span style=\'font-weight:normal;\rfont-style:normal\'>: the idea of fuzzyness</span></p>\r    <P><b><i>Ambient interfaces/Spatialised Media <o:p></o:p></i></b></p>\r    \r  <P><b><i>Data muttering</i></b>: just really like the word muttering - the idea \r    that the data is happily conversing with its self</p>\r    <h2>Theory</h2>\r    <P>The idea that the actions are affirmed through the system \r      - creating an environment for action defined through a mutual learning process \r      sited between the user and the environment itself. This reciprocal process \r      allows the environment to come into existence through the actions of the \r      user.</p>\r    \r  <ul style=\'margin-top:0cm\' type=disc>\r    <li class=MsoNormal style=\'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo2;tab-stops:list 36.0pt\'>The \r      question is how is this framed: in <i>Kaleidoscope</i><span\r     style=\'font-style:normal\'> it is like a toy - but also not very culturally \r      engaging.</span></li>\r    <li class=MsoNormal style=\'mso-list:l2 level1 lfo2;tab-stops:list 36.0pt\'>How \r      can it engage the body: what are the other interfaces that we could build \r      (do you move on the surface?)<o:p></o:p><o:p></o:p></li>\r  </ul>\r    <h2>Questions </h2>\r    <P>What is the difference between our fuzzy pattern recognition \r      combined with the Dynamic Feedback Mapper and reinforcement learning?</p>\r    <P>What is the difference between genetic programming and \r      fuzzy logic: do we want it to be genetic?</p>\r    \r  <h2><o:p></o:p></h2>\r    <p>&nbsp;</p>\r  <p>&nbsp;</p>\r  <p>&nbsp;</p>\r  <p>&nbsp;</p>\r  <p>&nbsp;</p>\r</div>\r  <div style=\'mso-element:footnote-list\'>\r<div style=\'mso-element:footnote\' id=ftn1>\r    <p class=MsoFootnoteText>&nbsp;</p>\r    </div>\r  </div>\r  <h3>&nbsp;</h3>\r  </div>\r<div id="Layer3" style="position:absolute; left:95px; top:270px; width:175px; height:200px; z-index:3"> \r  <table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">\r    <tr> \r      <td><h1 align="right">Kaleidoscope</h1>\r        <p align="right"><a href="kaleidoscopedesign_p1.html">Overview</a></p>\r        <p align="right"><a href="kaleidoscope.html">Idea </a></p>\r        <p align="right"><a href="kaleidoscope_programming.html">Programming ideas</a></p></td>\r    </tr>\r  </table>\r  <h1>&nbsp;</h1>\r  <p>&nbsp;</p>\r</div>\r</body>\r</html>\r',
